phonegame
Class GameDashboard

java.lang.Object
  phonegame.GameDashboard

public class GameDashboard
extends java.lang.Object

This class visually represents the "dashboard" in you game. You can use this dashboard to display all sorts of status information like, for example: the amount of health, power, etc.

Version:
2.0, October 11, 2005, 2.1, April 24, 2006, 3.0, November 17, 2006
Author:
Tim Prijn, Richard Kettelerij & Paul Bergervoet

Method Detail

addItem

public void addItem(java.lang.String label,
                    java.lang.String value)
Adds a new display-item to the dashboard. A display-item consists of a label (the name of the item) and a value. Both are Strings.
For example, to show points, make the label "Points" and the value at start "0". Later on, you can change the value of a display-item with a given name.

Parameters:
label - the label of this item, try to keep this short (e.g use LP instead of Lifepoints).
value - the value of this item

deleteItem

public void deleteItem(java.lang.String label)
Deletes a display-item from the dashboard

Parameters:
label - the label name of the item (serves as a 'key')

getItemValue

public java.lang.String getItemValue(java.lang.String label)
Gets the value property of a display-item on the dashboard

Parameters:
label - the label name of the item (serves as a 'key')
Returns:
the current value, as a String

paint

public void paint(javax.microedition.lcdui.Graphics g)
Draws the dashboard on the screen.

Note: If you want to create a more fancy dashboard you'll need to override this method with your own implementation.

Parameters:
g - the Graphics object of the GameWindow

setBackgroundColor

public void setBackgroundColor(int red,
                               int green,
                               int blue)
Sets the background color of the dashboard. The default color is black. If you don't want to use a background color set the RGB values to -1 (transparent)

Parameters:
red - the red RGB component
blue - the blue RGB component
green - the green RGB component

setFont

public void setFont(boolean bold,
                    boolean italic,
                    boolean underline)
Sets the font-properties of the text on the dashboard. You can switch on/off: Bold, italic and underline.

Parameters:
bold - true, if text should appear bold
italic - true, if text should appear italic
underline - true, if text should appear underlined

setItemValue

public void setItemValue(java.lang.String label,
                         java.lang.String value)
Sets the value property of a display-item on the dashboard. If there is no display-item with the given label, nothing is shown.

Parameters:
label - the label name of the item (serves as a 'key')

setLineColor

public void setLineColor(int red,
                         int green,
                         int blue,
                         boolean dotted)
Sets the line color of the dashboard. The default color is black. If you don't want to use a line color set the RGB values to -1 (transparent)

Parameters:
red - the red RGB component
blue - the blue RGB component
green - the green RGB component
dotted - true if the border should be drawn as a dotted line
